# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conan-cpp
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conan-cpp/2] This is the user documentation for Conan, an open source, decentralized C/C++ package manager that works in all platforms and with all build systems and compilers.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ was designed with systems programming and embedded, resource-constrained software and large systems in mind, with performance, efficiency, and flexibility of use as its design highlights.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ is standardized by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), with the latest standard version ratified and published by ISO in October 2024 as *ISO/IEC 14882:2024* (informally known as C++23).
[src:conan-cpp/c] The C++ programming language was initially standardized in 1998 as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which was then amended by the C++03, C++11, C++14, C++17, and C++20 standards.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The next C++23 standard superseded these with new features and an enlarged standard library.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Before the initial standardization in 1998, C++ was developed by Stroustrup at Bell Labs since 1979 as an extension of the C language; he wanted an efficient and flexible language similar to C that also provided high-level features for program organization.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Since 2012, C++ has been on a three-year release schedule with C++29 as the next planned standard.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1979, Bjarne Stroustrup, a Danish computer scientist, began work on "C with Classes", the predecessor to C++.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The motivation for creating a new language originated from Stroustrup's experience in programming for his PhD thesis.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Stroustrup found that Simula had features that were very helpful for large software development, but the language was too slow for practical use, while BCPL was fast but too low-level to be suitable for large software development.
[src:conan-cpp/c] When Stroustrup started working in AT&T Bell Labs, he had the problem of analyzing the UNIX kernel with respect to distributed computing.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Remembering his PhD experience, Stroustrup set out to enhance the C language with Simula-like features.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C was chosen because it was general-purpose, fast, portable, and widely used.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In addition to C and Simula's influences, other languages influenced this new language, including ALGOL 68, Ada, CLU, and ML.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Initially, Stroustrup's "C with Classes" added features to the C compiler, Cpre, including classes, derived classes, strong typing, inlining, and default arguments.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1982, Stroustrup began designing a cleaned-up and extended successor to C with Classes, using traditional compiler technology.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The language was briefly called C84 before the name C++ was adopted; the name was suggested by Rick Mascitti and refers to C's `++` increment operator.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The resulting language included virtual functions, function and operator overloading, references, `const`, improved type checking, user-controlled free-store memory allocation (`new`/`delete`), and BCPL-style single-line `//` comments.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Stroustrup also designed and implemented Cfront, the C++ compiler front end, between spring 1982 and summer 1983.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1984, Stroustrup implemented the first stream input/output library.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The idea of providing an output operator rather than a named output function was suggested by Doug McIlroy (who had previously suggested Unix pipes).
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1985, the first edition of *The C++ Programming Language* was released, which became the definitive reference for the language, as there was not yet an official standard.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The first commercial implementation of C++ was released in October of the same year.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1989, C++ 2.0 was released, followed by the updated second edition of *The C++ Programming Language* in 1991.
[src:conan-cpp/c] New features in 2.0 included multiple inheritance, abstract classes, static member functions, const member functions, and protected members.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1990, *The Annotated C++ Reference Manual* was published.
[src:conan-cpp/c] This work became the basis for the future standard.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Later feature additions included templates, exceptions, namespaces, new casts, and a Boolean type.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1998, C++98 was released, standardizing the language, and a minor update (C++03) was released in 2003.
[src:conan-cpp/c] After C++98, C++ evolved relatively slowly until, in 2011, the C++11 standard was released, adding numerous new features, enlarging the standard library further, and providing more facilities to C++ programmers.
[src:conan-cpp/c] After a minor C++14 update released in December 2014, various new additions were introduced in C++17.
[src:conan-cpp/c] After becoming finalized in February 2020, a draft of the C++20 standard was approved on 4 September 2020, and officially published on 15 December 2020.
[src:conan-cpp/c] On January 3, 2018, Stroustrup was announced as the 2018 winner of the Charles Stark Draper Prize for Engineering, "for conceptualizing and developing the C++ programming language".
[src:conan-cpp/c] In December 2022, C++ ranked third on the TIOBE index, surpassing Java for the first time in the history of the index.
[src:conan-cpp/c] As of November 2024, the language ranks second after Python, with Java being in third.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In March 2025, Stroustrup issued a call for the language community to defend it.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Since the language allows manual memory management, bugs that represent security risks such as buffer overflow may be introduced in programs when inadvertently misused by the programmer.
[src:conan-cpp/c] According to Stroustrup, "the name signifies the evolutionary nature of the changes from C." This name is credited to Rick Mascitti (mid-1983) and was first used in December 1983.
[src:conan-cpp/c] When Mascitti was questioned informally in 1992 about the naming, he indicated that it was given in a tongue-in-cheek spirit.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The name comes from C's `++` operator (which increments the value of a variable) and a common naming convention of using "+" to indicate an enhanced computer program.
[src:conan-cpp/c] During C++'s development period, the language had been referred to as "new C" and "C with Classes" before acquiring its final name.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ is standardized by an ISO working group known as JTC1/SC22/WG21.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The working group holds three week-long meetings each year.
[src:conan-cpp/c] So far, it has published seven revisions of the C++ standard and is currently working on the next revision, C++26.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 1998, the ISO working group standardized C++ for the first time as *ISO/IEC 14882:1998*, which is informally known as *C++98*.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 2003, it published a new version of the C++ standard called *ISO/IEC 14882:2003*, which fixed problems identified in C++98.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The next major revision of the standard was informally referred to as "C++0x", but it was not released until 2011.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++11 (14882:2011) included many additions to both the core language and the standard library.
[src:conan-cpp/c] In 2014, C++14 (also known as C++1y) was released as a small extension to C++11, featuring mainly bug fixes and small improvements.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The Draft International Standard ballot procedures completed in mid-August 2014.
[src:conan-cpp/c] After C++14, a major revision C++17, informally known as C++1z, was completed by the ISO C++ committee in mid July 2017 and was approved and published in December 2017.
[src:conan-cpp/c] More technical specifications are in development and pending approval.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The C++ language has two main components: a direct mapping of hardware features provided primarily by the C subset, and zero-overhead abstractions based on those mappings.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Stroustrup describes C++ as "a light-weight abstraction programming language [designed] for building and using efficient and elegant abstractions"; and "offering both hardware access and abstraction is the basis of C++.
[src:conan-cpp/c] A hello world program that conforms to the C standard is also a valid C++ hello world program.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The C++ standard specifies both the core language and the standard library.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The library clauses describe the contents of the library, how a well-formed C++ program uses it, and the requirements placed on conforming implementations.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The standard library is organized into areas such as language support, diagnostics, memory management, metaprogramming, general utilities, containers, iterators, ranges, algorithms, strings, text processing, numerics, time, input/output, and concurrency support.
[src:conan-cpp/c] It also provides the facilities of the C standard library through C++ headers such as `<cstdio>` and `<cstdlib>`; except for names defined as macros in C, these declarations are placed in namespace `std`.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Library facilities are traditionally made available by including standard headers, for example `#include <vector>`.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Since C++20, importable standard library headers may also be imported as header units.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++23 added the named standard library modules `std` and `std.compat`: `std` exports declarations in namespace `std`, while `std.compat` also exports corresponding global namespace declarations for C library facilities.
[src:conan-cpp/c] A major influence on the standard library was the Standard Template Library (STL), a generic programming library proposed to the C++ standards committee by Alexander Stepanov and Meng Lee in 1994.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Its model of containers, iterators, and generic algorithms became part of the Standard C++ Library, although the standard library also includes many other facilities, such as input/output, localization, diagnostics, and the C library subset.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The main aim is to efficiently and consistently write type and resource safe C++.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Despite this, the guidelines are not endorsed by the ISO C++ standards committee and do not represent the consensus of the committee.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The Core Guidelines were announced in the opening keynote at CPPCon 2015.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The Guidelines are accompanied by the Guideline Support Library (GSL), a header-only library of types and functions to implement the Core Guidelines and static checker tools for enforcing Guideline rules.
[src:conan-cpp/c] One of the largest implementations of this is Microsoft's implementation.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Many of the existing features in the GSL have been later integrated into the language, such as `std::byte`, smart pointers, and `std::span`.
[src:conan-cpp/c] To give compiler vendors greater freedom, the C++ standards committee decided not to dictate the implementation of name mangling, exception handling, and other implementation-specific features.
[src:conan-cpp/c] The downside of this decision is that object code produced by different compilers is expected to be incompatible.
[src:conan-cpp/c] There are, however, attempts to standardize compilers for particular machines or operating systems.
[src:conan-cpp/c] For example, the Itanium C++ ABI is processor-independent (despite its name) and is implemented by GCC and Clang.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ is often considered to be a superset of C but this is not strictly true.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Most C code can easily be made to compile correctly in C++ but there are a few differences that cause some valid C code to be invalid or behave differently in C++.
[src:conan-cpp/c] For example, C allows implicit conversion from `void*` to other pointer types but C++ does not (for type safety reasons).
[src:conan-cpp/c] Also, C++ defines many new keywords, such as `new` and `class`, which may be used as identifiers (for example, variable names) in a C program.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Some incompatibilities have been removed by the 1999 revision of the C standard (C99), which now supports C++ features such as line comments (`//`) and declarations mixed with code.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Some of the C99-introduced features were included in the subsequent version of the C++ standard, C++11 (out of those which were not redundant).
[src:conan-cpp/c] However, the C++11 standard introduces new incompatibilities, such as disallowing assignment of a string literal to a character pointer, which remains valid C.
[src:conan-cpp/c] To intermix C and C++ code, any function declaration or definition that is to be called from/used both in C and C++ must be declared with C linkage by placing it within an `extern "C" {/*...*/}` block.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Such a function may not rely on features depending on name mangling (i.e., function overloading).
[src:conan-cpp/c] Programs developed in C or C++ often utilize inline assembly to take advantage of its low-level functionalities, greater speed, and enhanced control compared to high-level programming languages when optimizing for performance is essential.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ provides support for embedding assembly language using asm declarations, but the compatibility of inline assembly varies significantly between compilers and architectures.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Unlike high-level language features such as Python or Java, assembly code is highly dependent on the underlying processor and compiler implementation.
[src:conan-cpp/c] Different C++ compilers implement inline assembly in distinct ways.
[src:conan-cpp/c] C++ provides two primary methods of integrating ASM code: standalone assembly files, where assembly code is written separately and linked with C++ code.
[src:conan-cpp/c] And inline assembly, where assembly code is embedded within C++ code using compiler-specific extensions.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] This section shows how to build your projects using Conan to manage your dependencies.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] We will begin with a basic example of a C project that uses CMake and depends on the **zlib** library.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] This project will use a *conanfile.txt* file to declare its dependencies.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] We will also cover how you can not only use ‘regular’ libraries with Conan but also manage tools you may need to use while building: like CMake, msys2, MinGW, etc.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] Then, we will explain different Conan concepts like settings and options and how you can use them to build your projects for different configurations like Debug, Release, with static or shared libraries, etc.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] Also, we will explain how to transition from the *conanfile.txt* file we used in the first example to a more powerful *conanfile.py*.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] After that, we will introduce the concept of Conan build and host profiles and explain how you can use them to cross-compile your application to different platforms.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] Then, in the “Introduction to versioning” we will learn about using different versions, defining requirements with version ranges, the concept of revisions and a brief introduction to lockfiles to achieve reproducibility of the dependency graph.
[src:conan-cpp/consuming-packages] The Conan 2 Essentials training course is available for free at the JFrog Academy, which covers the same topics as this documentation but in a more interactive way.
[src:conan-cpp/creating-packages] This section shows how to create Conan packages using a Conan recipe.
[src:conan-cpp/creating-packages] We begin by creating a basic Conan recipe to package a simple C++ library that you can scaffold using the **conan new** command.
[src:conan-cpp/creating-packages] After this walkthrough around some Conan recipe methods, we will explain some peculiarities of different types of Conan packages like, for example, header-only libraries, packages for pre-built binaries, packaging tools for building other packages or packaging your own applications.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:conan-cpp/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:conan-cpp/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
